The Adamawa state government has confirmed the death a 29-year-old women from Lassa fever outbreak in the state. Prof Abdullahi Isa, Commissioner for Health and Humanitarian services, told journalist in Yola Tuesday that, the deceased relation provided care for the victim. He said the women who hails from Numan local government of the state, was first seen as a gravid patient in a private health facility in Yola on the 18th of January. He said, three others whose blood sample were tested free were discharge. “As at today, there was no cases of admission in connection with the lassa fever in the state. “Emergency operation centre for management of response activities on daily bases, has been set up to be replicated, across the councils of the state. Massive state wide public enlightenment campaign on prevention and control measures. “More drugs, PPEs and supplies are been produced and pre-positioned to support case a management services. Alert signal have been sent to all our disease surveillance and notification officers. “The re-orientation of our health facility staff on infection, prevention and control practices and case management has since commenced”. The commissioner advised people to set traps or keep cats to chase away rodents, he added. 